recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural vocalization. Calling from the edge of the mown path and moving around in 1m tall grass, frequently coming out in the open. Distance from microphone ~8m. Same individual as XC291258.

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

#Editing#
Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, cutoff 700 Hz, order 3

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.rmk: Same individual as recorded in XC425109.  Habitat is taconite tailings basin, inactive since 2001, restored to non-native grasses and legumes, with very scattered low shrubs. Although the recording area was a shallow wetland for several years, it drained three years ago and is now dry upland. We counted at least 15 singing males in the area. recordings.loc: Embarrass, St. Louis County, Minnesota
recordings.rmk: Habitat is taconite tailings basin, inactive since 2001, restored to non-native grasses and legumes, with very scattered low shrubs. Although the recording area was a shallow wetland for several years, it drained  three years ago and is now  dry upland. We counted at least 15 singing males in the area.  The recording is a pair agitated at my presence, presumably because I was near their nest or young. They flitted back and forth in such close proximity to each other I couldn't tell for sure if any of the three distinct calls heard were from the female. Same individual recorded in XC425112.

recordings.loc: Red River National Wildlife Refuge- Headquarters Unit, Bossier Parish, Louisiana
recordings.rmk: Southeast end of the refuge near Lake Caroline. I was approaching a small shrub in an open field adjacent riparian, wooded edge to attempt photo of a late Song Sparrow perched up within a small, leafless shrub with 4 Lincoln's Sparrow. Sedge Wren began singing, hidden from within profuse vetch. The Lincoln's were silent during the recording but sang much on and off during the walk.

recordings.loc: Peterborough, Peterborough County, Ontario

recordings.loc: Stockbridge, Berkshire County, Massachusetts
recordings.rmk: Cut frequencies below 1500 khz or so.  Otherwise, recording unedited.  Bird singing from the edge of a hay field with a marsh deep enough for Marsh Wrens and Virginia Rails.  Excellent listening conditions with light winds.  Note variability in the songs--quite interesting to hear several song types.
